Practically all get remarried at some point during their lifetimes. However, in their response to an interview question about whether or not they remarried, males most frequently responded in the negative. The frequency of males who responded in the negative is different. By gender, the percentage of women to reply in the negative is 25.20 percent in unmarrried, 25.00 percent in newly married, and 9.15 percent in married groups. Thus females in all stages are most likely to be unmarried, through compared to men who may be unmarried after divorce, women are less likely to marry again.
In contrast, married and newly/more recently married males most frequently reported that they live with family who are siblings, cousins, parents, or grandchildren. Males who reported to be in the unmarried group most frequently responded that they live with family members who are friends, siblings, or sons of siblings.
